body:
@siphiuel,
> If you comment it away, then it makes things worse

I would say it did not make any difference at all, it was around same 2 mins time. As default `keepAliveInterval` is 2 secs (much less than 2 mins already) I doubt that descreasing it would help here.

@cammellos, 
> as we did in waku-1

yep the issue is not reproducible in pub chats on the old release version which uses waku-1 as far as I understand.

> @siphiuel I think the issue here is that we don't have acknowledgements from other peers, as we did in waku-1, so messages are marked as sent if the _leave_ the node, but it could be that we are writing on a dead connection that we haven't realized is dead (i.e an half open socket).

Right. That is why in `startKeepAlive` we're doing the pinging via libp2p's Ping protocol, as this seems to be the good way to find out if the peer is responding and the connection is still alive.

@rasom so after going to flight mode there's a ~2min interval when all messages being sent are lost, disregarding whatever keepAliveInterval we have or if we even have it running? And after 2 mins elapse message can be resent once the connection is back?

@siphiuel 

> so after going to flight mode there's a ~2min interval when all messages being sent are lost, disregarding whatever keepAliveInterval we have or if we even have it running? And after 2 mins elapse message can be resent once the connection is back?

That is correct. It also can be observer on "Peers stats" screen (on mobile) as "Peers count" slowly decreases to zero during those ~2 mins.

@siphiuel 
1. I was wrong and `keepAliveInterval` was 10s, not 2s. 
2. Decreasing it to 2s shortens the gap when message is sent and lost but doesn't remove the gap completely. Idk if that is actually desirable to make this interval much shorter or even shorter than 10s.

@richard-ramos @cammellos 
What if on reaching zero peers we mark all messages which were sent in last 1-2mins as not sent so that those are resent on reconnection. This sounds dumb and is not 100% reliable but likely will fix some of issues here.
